[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] In computing, the **count–min sketch** (**CM sketch**) is a probabilistic data structure that serves as a frequency table of events in a stream of data.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] It uses hash functions to map events to frequencies, but unlike a hash table uses only sub-linear space, at the expense of overcounting some events due to collisions.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] The count–min sketch was invented in 2003 by Graham Cormode and S.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] Muthu Muthukrishnan and described by them in a 2005 paper.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] Count–min sketch is an alternative to count sketch and AMS sketch and can be considered an implementation of a counting Bloom filter (Fan et al., 1998) or multistage-filter.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] However, they are used differently and therefore sized differently: a count–min sketch typically has a sublinear number of cells, related to the desired approximation quality of the sketch, while a counting Bloom filter is more typically sized to match the number of elements in the set.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] The goal of the basic version of the count–min sketch is to consume a stream of events, one at a time, and count the frequency of the different types of events in the stream.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] At any time, the sketch can be queried for the frequency of a particular event type i from a universe of event types ${\mathcal {U}}$ , and will return an estimate of this frequency that is within a certain distance of the true frequency, with a certain probability.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] The actual sketch data structure is a two-dimensional array of w columns and d rows.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] The parameters w and d are fixed when the sketch is created, and determine the time and space needs and the probability of error when the sketch is queried for a frequency or inner product.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] Associated with each of the d rows is a separate hash function; the hash functions must be pairwise independent.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] The parameters w and d can be chosen by setting *w* = ⌈*e*/*ε*⌉ and *d* = ⌈ln 1/*δ*⌉, where the error in answering a query is within an additive factor of ε with probability 1 − *δ* (see below), and *e* is Euler's number.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] When a new event of type i arrives we update as follows: for each row j of the table, apply the corresponding hash function to obtain a column index *k* = *h**j*(*i*).
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] Then increment the value in row j, column k by one.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] The *point query* asks for the count of an event type i.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] The estimated count is given by the least value in the table for i, namely ${\hat {a}}_{i}=\min _{j}\mathrm {count} [j,h_{j}(i)]$ , where $\mathrm {count}$ is the table.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] Obviously, for each i, one has $a_{i}\leq {\hat {a}}_{i}$ , where $a_{i}$ is the true frequency with which i occurred in the stream.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] Additionally, this estimate has the guarantee that ${\hat {a}}_{i}\leq a_{i}+\varepsilon N$ with probability $1-\delta$ , where $N=\sum _{i\in {\mathcal {U}}}a_{i}$ is the stream size, i.e. the total number of items seen by the sketch.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] An *inner product query* asks for the inner product between the histograms represented by two count–min sketches, $\mathrm {count} _{a}$ and $\mathrm {count} _{b}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] The inner product can then be estimated as ${\widehat {a\cdot b}}=\min _{j}{\widehat {a\cdot b}}_{j}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] Like the count sketch, the Count–min sketch is a linear sketch.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] That is, given two streams, constructing a sketch on each stream and summing the sketches yields the same result as concatenating the streams and constructing a sketch on the concatenated streams.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] This makes the sketch mergeable and appropriate for use in distributed settings in addition to streaming ones.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] One potential problem with the usual min estimator for count–min sketches is that they are biased estimators of the true frequency of events: they may overestimate, but never underestimate the true count in a point query.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] Furthermore, while the min estimator works well when the distribution is highly skewed, other sketches such as the Count sketch based on means are more accurate when the distribution is not sufficiently skewed.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] Several variations on the sketch have been proposed to reduce error and reduce or eliminate bias.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] To remove bias, the `hCount*` estimator repeatedly randomly selects d random entries in the sketch and takes the minimum to obtain an unbiased estimate of the bias and subtracts it off.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] A maximum likelihood estimator (MLE) was derived in Ting.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] By using the MLE, the estimator is always able to match or better the min estimator and works well even if the distribution is not skewed.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] This paper also showed the hCount* debiasing operation is a bootstrapping procedure that can be efficiently computed without random sampling and can be generalized to any estimator.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] Since errors arise from hash collisions with unknown items from the universe, several approaches correct for the collisions when multiple elements of the universe are known or queried for simultaneously .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/count-min-sketch] For each of these, a large proportion of the universe must be known to observe a significant benefit.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] In machine learning, **feature hashing**, also known as the **hashing trick** (by analogy to the kernel trick), is a fast and space-efficient way of vectorizing features, i.e. turning arbitrary features into indices in a vector or matrix.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] It works by applying a hash function to the features and using their hash values as indices directly (after a modulo operation), rather than looking the indices up in an associative array.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] In addition to its use for encoding non-numeric values, feature hashing can also be used for dimensionality reduction.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] This trick is often attributed to Weinberger et al.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] (2009), but there exists a much earlier description of this method published by John Moody in 1989.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] In a typical document classification task, the input to the machine learning algorithm (both during learning and classification) is free text.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] From this, a bag of words (BOW) representation is constructed: the individual tokens are extracted and counted, and each distinct token in the training set defines a feature (independent variable) of each of the documents in both the training and test sets.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Machine learning algorithms, however, are typically defined in terms of numerical vectors.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Therefore, the bags of words for a set of documents is regarded as a term-document matrix where each row is a single document, and each column is a single feature/word; the entry *i*, *j* in such a matrix captures the frequency (or weight) of the j'th term of the *vocabulary* in document i.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] (An alternative convention swaps the rows and columns of the matrix, but this difference is immaterial.) Typically, these vectors are extremely sparse—according to Zipf's law.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] The common approach is to construct, at learning time or prior to that, a *dictionary* representation of the vocabulary of the training set, and use that to map words to indices.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Hash tables and tries are common candidates for dictionary implementation.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] The problem with this process is that such dictionaries take up a large amount of storage space and grow in size as the training set grows.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] On the contrary, if the vocabulary is kept fixed and not increased with a growing training set, an adversary may try to invent new words or misspellings that are not in the stored vocabulary so as to circumvent a machine learned filter.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Research attempted to use feature hashing for their spam filters.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Note that the hashing trick isn't limited to text classification and similar tasks at the document level, but can be applied to any problem that involves large (perhaps unbounded) numbers of features.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Mathematically, a token is an element t in a finite (or countably infinite) set T .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Suppose we only need to process a finite corpus, then we can put all tokens appearing in the corpus into T , meaning that T is finite.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] However, suppose we want to process all possible words made of the English letters, then T is countably infinite.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Most neural networks can only operate on real vector inputs, so we must construct a "dictionary" function $\phi :T\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] When T is finite, of size $|T|=m\leq n$ , then we can use one-hot encoding to map it into $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] In other words, we assign a unique index i to each token, then map the token with index i to the unit basis vector $e_{i}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] One-hot encoding is easy to interpret, but it requires one to maintain the arbitrary enumeration of T .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Given a token $t\in T$ , to compute $\phi (t)$ , we must find out the index i of the token t .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Thus, to implement $\phi$ efficiently, we need a fast-to-compute bijection $h:T\to \{1,...,m\}$ , then we have $\phi (t)=e_{h(t)}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] In fact, we can relax the requirement slightly: It suffices to have a fast-to-compute *injection* $h:T\to \{1,...,n\}$ , then use $\phi (t)=e_{h(t)}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] In practice, there is no simple way to construct an efficient injection $h:T\to \{1,...,n\}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] However, we do not need a strict injection, but only an *approximate* injection.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] That is, when $t\neq t'$ , we should *probably* have $h(t)\neq h(t')$ , so that *probably* $\phi (t)\neq \phi (t')$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] At this point, we have just specified that h should be a hashing function.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Thus we reach the idea of feature hashing.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] The basic feature hashing algorithm presented in (Weinberger et al.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] We want to say something about the geometric property of $\phi$ , but T , by itself, is just a set of tokens, we cannot impose a geometric structure on it except the discrete topology, which is generated by the discrete metric.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] There are essentially only two ways to handle infinities.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] One may impose a metric, then take its completion, to allow well-behaved infinite sums, or one may demand that nothing is actually infinite, only potentially so.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Here, we go for the potential-infinity way, by restricting $\mathbb {R} ^{T}$ to contain only vectors with finite support: $\forall (x_{t})_{t\in T}\in \mathbb {R} ^{T}$ , only finitely many entries of $(x_{t})_{t\in T}$ are nonzero.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Taking its completion would get us to a Hilbert space, which allows well-behaved infinite sums.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Now we have an inner product space, with enough structure to describe the geometry of the feature hashing function $\phi :\mathbb {R} ^{T}\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] The above statement and proof interprets the binary hash function $\zeta$ not as a deterministic function of type $T\to \{-1,+1\}$ , but as a random binary vector $\{-1,+1\}^{T}$ with unbiased entries, meaning that $Pr(\zeta (t)=+1)=Pr(\zeta (t)=-1)={\frac {1}{2}}$ for any $t\in T$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] This is a good intuitive picture, though not rigorous.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Instead of maintaining a dictionary, a feature vectorizer that uses the hashing trick can build a vector of a pre-defined length by applying a hash function h to the features (e.g., words), then using the hash values directly as feature indices and updating the resulting vector at those indices.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Here, we assume that feature actually means feature vector.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Thus, if our feature vector is ["cat","dog","cat"] and hash function is $h(x_{f})=1$ if $x_{f}$ is "cat" and 2 if $x_{f}$ is "dog".
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Let us take the output feature vector dimension (N) to be 4.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] It has been suggested that a second, single-bit output hash function ξ be used to determine the sign of the update value, to counter the effect of hash collisions.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] The above pseudocode actually converts each sample into a vector.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] An optimized version would instead only generate a stream of $(h,\zeta )$ pairs and let the learning and prediction algorithms consume such streams; a linear model can then be implemented as a single hash table representing the coefficient vector.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Feature hashing generally suffers from hash collision, which means that there exist pairs of different tokens with the same hash: $t\neq t',\phi (t)=\phi (t')=v$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] A machine learning model trained on feature-hashed words would then have difficulty distinguishing t and $t'$ , essentially because v is polysemic.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] If $t'$ is rare, then performance degradation is small, as the model could always just ignore the rare case, and pretend all v means t .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] However, if both are common, then the degradation can be serious.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] To handle this, one can train supervised hashing functions that avoids mapping common tokens to the same feature vectors.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Ganchev and Dredze showed that in text classification applications with random hash functions and several tens of thousands of columns in the output vectors, feature hashing need not have an adverse effect on classification performance, even without the signed hash function.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] (2015) combined the idea of feature hashing and sparse matrix to construct "virtual matrices": large matrices with small storage requirements.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] The idea is to treat a matrix $M\in \mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ as a dictionary, with keys in $n\times n$ , and values in $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] Then, as usual in hashed dictionaries, one can use a hash function $h:\mathbb {N} \times \mathbb {N} \to m$ , and thus represent a matrix as a vector in $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ , no matter how big n is.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/feature-hashing] With virtual matrices, they constructed *HashedNets*, which are large neural networks taking only small amounts of storage.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] In the original paper by Flajolet *et al.* and in related literature on the count-distinct problem, the term "cardinality" is used to mean the number of distinct elements in a data stream with repeated elements.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] However in the theory of multisets the term refers to the sum of multiplicities of each member of a multiset.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] This article chooses to use Flajolet's definition for consistency with the sources.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] The basis of the HyperLogLog algorithm is the observation that the cardinality of a multiset of uniformly distributed random numbers can be estimated by calculating the maximum number of leading zeros in the binary representation of each number in the set.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] If the maximum number of leading zeros observed is *n*, an estimate for the number of distinct elements in the set is 2*n*.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] In the HyperLogLog algorithm, a hash function is applied to each element in the original multiset to obtain a multiset of uniformly distributed random numbers with the same cardinality as the original multiset.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] The cardinality of this randomly distributed set can then be estimated using the algorithm above.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] The simple estimate of cardinality obtained using the algorithm above has the disadvantage of a large variance.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] The HyperLogLog has three main operations: **add** to add a new element to the set, **count** to obtain the cardinality of the set and **merge** to obtain the union of two sets.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] Some derived operations can be computed using the inclusion–exclusion principle like the **cardinality of the intersection** or the **cardinality of the difference** between two HyperLogLogs combining the merge and count operations.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] The data of the HyperLogLog is stored in an array M of m counters (or "registers") that are initialized to 0.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] The add operation consists of computing the hash of the input data v with a hash function h, getting the first b bits (where b is ${\textstyle \log _{2}(m)}$ ), and adding 1 to them to obtain the address of the register to modify (assuming 1-based indexing).
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] With the remaining bits as w, compute ${\textstyle \rho (w)}$ which returns the position of the leftmost 1, where leftmost position is 1 (in other words: number of leading zeros plus 1).
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] The new value of the register will be the maximum between the current value of the register and ${\textstyle \rho (w)}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] The intuition is that n being the unknown cardinality of M, each subset ${\textstyle M_{j}}$ will have ${\textstyle n/m}$ elements.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] The harmonic mean of 2 to these quantities is ${\textstyle mZ}$ which should be near ${\textstyle n/m}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] Thus, ${\textstyle m^{2}Z}$ should be n approximately.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] Finally, the constant ${\textstyle \alpha _{m}}$ is introduced to correct a systematic multiplicative bias present in ${\textstyle m^{2}Z}$ due to hash collisions.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] The HyperLogLog technique, though, is biased for small cardinalities below a threshold of ${\textstyle {\frac {5}{2}}m}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] The original paper proposes using a different algorithm for small cardinalities known as Linear Counting.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] If ${\textstyle V=0}$ , use the standard HyperLogLog estimator ${\textstyle E}$ above.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] With the above corrections for lower and upper bounds, the error can be estimated as ${\textstyle \sigma =1.04/{\sqrt {m}}}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] To analyze the complexity, the data streaming $(\epsilon ,\delta )$ model is used, which analyzes the space necessary to get a $1\pm \epsilon$ approximation with a fixed success probability $1-\delta$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] The relative error of HLL is $1.04/{\sqrt {m}}$ and it needs $O(\epsilon ^{-2}\log \log n+\log n)$ space, where n is the set cardinality and m is the number of registers (usually less than one byte size).
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] The **add** operation depends on the size of the output of the hash function.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] As this size is fixed, we can consider the running time for the add operation to be $O(1)$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] The **count** and **merge** operations depend on the number of registers m and have a theoretical cost of $O(m)$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] In some implementations (Redis) the number of registers is fixed and the cost is considered to be $O(1)$ in the documentation.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] When the data arrives in a single stream, the Historic Inverse Probability or martingale estimator significantly improves the accuracy of the HLL sketch and uses 36% less memory to achieve a given error level.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] This estimator is provably optimal for any duplicate insensitive approximate distinct counting sketch on a single stream.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] The single stream scenario also leads to variants in the HLL sketch construction.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/hyperloglog] HLL-TailCut+ uses 45% less memory than the original HLL sketch but at the cost of being dependent on the data insertion order and not being able to merge sketches.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] In computer science, **locality-sensitive hashing** (**LSH**) is a fuzzy hashing technique that hashes similar input items into the same "buckets" with high probability.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] The number of buckets is much smaller than the universe of possible input items.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Since similar items end up in the same buckets, this technique can be used for data clustering and nearest neighbor search.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] It differs from conventional hashing techniques in that hash collisions are maximized, not minimized.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Alternatively, the technique can be seen as a way to reduce the dimensionality of high-dimensional data; high-dimensional input items can be reduced to low-dimensional versions while preserving relative distances between items.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Hashing-based approximate nearest-neighbor search algorithms generally use one of two main categories of hashing methods: either data-independent methods, such as locality-sensitive hashing (LSH); or data-dependent methods, such as locality-preserving hashing (LPH).
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Locality-preserving hashing was initially devised as a way to facilitate data pipelining in implementations of massively parallel algorithms that use randomized routing and universal hashing to reduce memory contention and network congestion.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] if it satisfies the following condition.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Alternatively it is possible to define an LSH family on a universe of items U endowed with a similarity function $\phi \colon U\times U\to [0,1]$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] In this setting, a LSH scheme is a family of hash functions H coupled with a probability distribution D over H such that a function $h\in H$ chosen according to D satisfies $Pr[h(a)=h(b)]=\phi (a,b)$ for each $a,b\in U$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given a $(d_{1},d_{2},p_{1},p_{2})$ -sensitive family ${\mathcal {F}}$ , we can construct new families ${\mathcal {G}}$ by either the AND-construction or OR-construction of ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] To create an AND-construction, we define a new family ${\mathcal {G}}$ of hash functions g, where each function g is constructed from k random functions $h_{1},\ldots ,h_{k}$ from ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] To create an OR-construction, we define a new family ${\mathcal {G}}$ of hash functions g, where each function g is constructed from k random functions $h_{1},\ldots ,h_{k}$ from ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] We then say that for a hash function $g\in {\mathcal {G}}$ , $g(x)=g(y)$ if and only if $h_{i}(x)=h_{i}(y)$ for one or more values of i.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] One of the easiest ways to construct an LSH family is by bit sampling.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] This approach works for the Hamming distance over d-dimensional vectors $\{0,1\}^{d}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Here, the family ${\mathcal {F}}$ of hash functions is simply the family of all the projections of points on one of the d coordinates, i.e., ${\mathcal {F}}=\{h\colon \{0,1\}^{d}\to \{0,1\}\mid h(x)=x_{i}{\text{ for some }}i\in \{1,\ldots ,d\}\}$ , where $x_{i}$ is the i th coordinate of x .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] A random function h from ${\mathcal {F}}$ simply selects a random bit from the input point.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] That is, any two vectors $x,y$ with Hamming distance at most R collide under a random h with probability at least $P_{1}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Any $x,y$ with Hamming distance at least $cR$ collide with probability at most $P_{2}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Suppose U is composed of subsets of some ground set of enumerable items S and the similarity function of interest is the Jaccard index J.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] If π is a permutation on the indices of S, for $A\subseteq S$ let $h(A)=\min _{a\in A}\{\pi (a)\}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Each possible choice of π defines a single hash function h mapping input sets to elements of S.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Define the function family H to be the set of all such functions and let D be the uniform distribution.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given two sets $A,B\subseteq S$ the event that $h(A)=h(B)$ corresponds exactly to the event that the minimizer of π over $A\cup B$ lies inside $A\cap B$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] As h was chosen uniformly at random, $Pr[h(A)=h(B)]=J(A,B)\,$ and $(H,D)\,$ define an LSH scheme for the Jaccard index.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Because the symmetric group on n elements has size n!, choosing a truly random permutation from the full symmetric group is infeasible for even moderately sized n.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Because of this fact, there has been significant work on finding a family of permutations that is "min-wise independent" — a permutation family for which each element of the domain has equal probability of being the minimum under a randomly chosen π.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] It has been established that a min-wise independent family of permutations is at least of size $\operatorname {lcm} \{\,1,2,\ldots ,n\,\}\geq e^{n-o(n)}$ , and that this bound is tight.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Because min-wise independent families are too big for practical applications, two variant notions of min-wise independence are introduced: restricted min-wise independent permutations families, and approximate min-wise independent families.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Restricted min-wise independence is the min-wise independence property restricted to certain sets of cardinality at most k.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Approximate min-wise independence differs from the property by at most a fixed ε.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] The encoding must be robust against intentional attacks.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] The encoding should support an extremely low risk of false positives.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Testing performed in the paper on a range of file types identified the Nilsimsa hash as having a significantly higher false positive rate when compared to other similarity digest schemes such as TLSH, Ssdeep and Sdhash.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] An implementation of TLSH is available as open-source software.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] The random projection method of LSH due to Moses Charikar called SimHash (also sometimes called arccos) uses an approximation of the cosine distance between vectors.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] The technique was used to approximate the NP-complete max-cut problem.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] The basic idea of this technique is to choose a random hyperplane (defined by a normal unit vector r) at the outset and use the hyperplane to hash input vectors.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given an input vector v and a hyperplane defined by r, we let $h(v)=\operatorname {sgn}(v\cdot r)$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] That is, $h(v)=\pm 1$ depending on which side of the hyperplane v lies.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] This way, each possible choice of a random hyperplane r can be interpreted as a hash function $h(v)$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Since the ratio between ${\frac {\theta (u,v)}{\pi }}$ and $1-\cos(\theta (u,v))$ is at least 0.439 when $\theta (u,v)\in [0,\pi ]$ , the probability of two vectors being on different sides of the random hyperplane is approximately proportional to the cosine distance between them.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] The hash function $h_{\mathbf {a} ,b}({\boldsymbol {\upsilon }}):{\mathcal {R}}^{d}\to {\mathcal {N}}$ maps a d-dimensional vector ${\boldsymbol {\upsilon }}$ onto the set of integers.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Each hash function in the family is indexed by a choice of random $\mathbf {a}$ and b where $\mathbf {a}$ is a d-dimensional vector with entries chosen independently from a stable distribution and b is a real number chosen uniformly from the range [0,r].
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] For a fixed $\mathbf {a} ,b$ the hash function $h_{\mathbf {a} ,b}$ is given by $h_{\mathbf {a} ,b}({\boldsymbol {\upsilon }})=\left\lfloor {\frac {\mathbf {a} \cdot {\boldsymbol {\upsilon }}+b}{r}}\right\rfloor$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Other construction methods for hash functions have been proposed to better fit the data.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] In particular k-means hash functions are better in practice than projection-based hash functions, but without any theoretical guarantee.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Semantic hashing is a technique that attempts to map input items to addresses such that closer inputs have higher semantic similarity.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] The hashcodes are found via training of an artificial neural network or graphical model.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] One of the main applications of LSH is to provide a method for efficient approximate nearest neighbor search algorithms.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Consider an LSH family ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] The algorithm has two main parameters: the width parameter k and the number of hash tables L.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] In the first step, we define a new family ${\mathcal {G}}$ of hash functions g, where each function g is obtained by concatenating k functions $h_{1},\ldots ,h_{k}$ from ${\mathcal {F}}$ , i.e., $g(p)=[h_{1}(p),\ldots ,h_{k}(p)]$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] In other words, a random hash function g is obtained by concatenating k randomly chosen hash functions from ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] The algorithm then constructs L hash tables, each corresponding to a different randomly chosen hash function g.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] In the preprocessing step we hash all n d-dimensional points from the data set S into each of the L hash tables.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given that the resulting hash tables have only n non-zero entries, one can reduce the amount of memory used per each hash table to $O(n)$ using standard hash functions.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] Given a query point q, the algorithm iterates over the L hash functions g.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] For each g considered, it retrieves the data points that are hashed into the same bucket as q.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] The process is stopped as soon as a point within distance cR from q is found.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] To generalize the above algorithm without radius R being fixed, we can take the algorithm and do a sort of binary search over R.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] When t is large, it is possible to reduce the hashing time from $O(n^{\rho })$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] It is also sometimes the case that the factor $1/P_{1}$ can be very large.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] This happens for example with Jaccard similarity data, where even the most similar neighbor often has a quite low Jaccard similarity with the query.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/locality-sensitive-hashing] In it was shown how to reduce the query time to $O(n^{\rho }/P_{1}^{1-\rho })$ (not including hashing costs) and similarly the space usage.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] In computer science and data mining, **MinHash** (or the **min-wise independent permutations** locality sensitive hashing scheme) is a technique for quickly estimating how similar two sets are.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] The scheme was published by Andrei Broder in a 1997 conference, and initially used in the AltaVista search engine to detect duplicate web pages and eliminate them from search results.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] It has also been applied in large-scale clustering problems, such as clustering documents by the similarity of their sets of words.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] The Jaccard similarity coefficient is a commonly used indicator of the similarity between two sets.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] This value is 0 when the two sets are disjoint, 1 when they are equal, and strictly between 0 and 1 otherwise.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Two sets are more similar (i.e. have relatively more members in common) when their Jaccard index is closer to 1.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] The goal of MinHash is to estimate *J*(*A*,*B*) quickly, without explicitly computing the intersection and union.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Now, applying *h*min to both *A* and *B*, and assuming no hash collisions, we see that the values are equal (*h*min(*A*) = *h*min(*B*)) if and only if among all elements of $A\cup B$ , the element with the minimum hash value lies in the intersection $A\cap B$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] That is, the probability that *h*min(*A*) = *h*min(*B*) is true is equal to the similarity *J*(*A*,*B*), assuming drawing *perm* from a uniform distribution.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] In other words, if *r* is the random variable that is one when *h*min(*A*) = *h*min(*B*) and zero otherwise, then *r* is an unbiased estimator of *J*(*A*,*B*).
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] *r* has too high a variance to be a useful estimator for the Jaccard similarity on its own, because r is always zero or one.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] The idea of the MinHash scheme is to reduce this variance by averaging together several variables constructed in the same way.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] The simplest version of the minhash scheme uses *k* different hash functions, where *k* is a fixed integer parameter, and represents each set *S* by the *k* values of *h*min(*S*) for these *k* functions.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] To estimate *J*(*A*,*B*) using this version of the scheme, let *y* be the number of hash functions for which *h*min(*A*) = *h*min(*B*), and use *y*/*k* as the estimate.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] This estimate is the average of *k* different 0-1 random variables, each of which is one when *h*min(*A*) = *h*min(*B*) and zero otherwise, and each of which is an unbiased estimator of *J*(*A*,*B*).
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Therefore, their average is also an unbiased estimator, and by standard deviation for sums of 0-1 random variables, its expected error is O(1/√*k*).
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Therefore, for any constant ε > 0 there is a constant *k* = O(1/ε2) such that the expected error of the estimate is at most ε.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] For example, 400 hashes would be required to estimate *J*(*A*,*B*) with an expected error less than or equal to .05.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] It may be computationally expensive to compute multiple hash functions, but a related version of MinHash scheme avoids this penalty by using only a single hash function and uses it to select multiple values from each set rather than selecting only a single minimum value per hash function.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Let *h* be a hash function, and let *k* be a fixed integer.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] If *S* is any set of *k* or more values in the domain of *h*, define *h*(*k*)(*S*) to be the subset of the *k* members of *S* that have the smallest values of *h*.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] This subset *h*(*k*)(*S*) is used as a *signature* for the set *S*, and the similarity of any two sets is estimated by comparing their signatures.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Specifically, let *A* and *B* be any two sets.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Then *X* = *h*(*k*)(*h*(*k*)(*A*) ∪ *h*(*k*)(*B*)) = *h*(*k*)(*A* ∪ *B*) is a set of *k* elements of *A* ∪ *B*, and if *h* is a random function then any subset of *k* elements is equally likely to be chosen; that is, *X* is a simple random sample of *A* ∪ *B*.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] However, when *k* is small relative to the sizes of the sets, this difference is negligible.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] By standard Chernoff bounds for sampling without replacement, this estimator has expected error O(1/√*k*), matching the performance of the multiple-hash-function scheme.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] The estimator |*Y*|/*k* can be computed in time O(*k*) from the two signatures of the given sets, in either variant of the scheme.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Therefore, when ε and *k* are constants, the time to compute the estimated similarity from the signatures is also constant.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] The signature of each set can be computed in linear time on the size of the set, so when many pairwise similarities need to be estimated this method can lead to a substantial savings in running time compared to doing a full comparison of the members of each set.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Specifically, for set size *n* the many hash variant takes O(*n* *k*) time.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] The single hash variant is generally faster, requiring O(*n*) time to maintain the queue of minimum hash values assuming *n* >> *k*.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] A variety of techniques to introduce weights into the computation of MinHashes have been developed.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] The simplest extends it to integer weights.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Extend our hash function h to accept both a set member and an integer, then generate multiple hashes for each item, according to its weight.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] If item i occurs n times, generate hashes $h(i,1),h(i,2),\ldots ,h(i,n)$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Run the original algorithm on this expanded set of hashes.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Doing so yields the weighted Jaccard Index as the collision probability.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Further extensions that achieve this collision probability on real weights with better runtime have been developed, one for dense data, and another for sparse data.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Another family of extensions use exponentially distributed hashes.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] A uniformly random hash between 0 and 1 can be converted to follow an exponential distribution by CDF inversion.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] This method exploits the many beautiful properties of the minimum of a set of exponential variables.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] In order to implement the MinHash scheme as described above, one needs the hash function *h* to define a random permutation on *n* elements, where *n* is the total number of distinct elements in the union of all of the sets to be compared.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] But because there are *n*! different permutations, it would require Ω(*n* log *n*) bits just to specify a truly random permutation, an infeasibly large number for even moderate values of *n*.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Because of this fact, by analogy to the theory of universal hashing, there has been significant work on finding a family of permutations that is "min-wise independent", meaning that for any subset of the domain, any element is equally likely to be the minimum.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] different permutations, and therefore that it needs Ω(*n*) bits to specify a single permutation, still infeasibly large.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Because of the above impracticality, two variant notions of min-wise independence have been introduced: restricted min-wise independent permutations families, and approximate min-wise independent families.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Restricted min-wise independence is the min-wise independence property restricted to certain sets of cardinality at most *k*.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Approximate min-wise independence has at most a fixed probability ε of varying from full independence.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] In 1999 Piotr Indyk proved that any k-wise independent family of hash functions is also approximately min-wise independent for k large enough.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] for all sets $|X|\leq \epsilon nc'$ and $x\not \in X$ .
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] This guarantee is, among other things, sufficient to give the Jaccard bound required by the MinHash algorithm.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Since k-wise independent hash functions can be specified using just $k\log n$ bits, this approach is much more practical than using completely min-wise independent permutations.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Another practical family of hash functions that give approximate min-wise independence is Tabulation hashing.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] The original applications for MinHash involved clustering and eliminating near-duplicates among web documents, represented as sets of the words occurring in those documents.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Similar techniques have also been used for clustering and near-duplicate elimination for other types of data, such as images: in the case of image data, an image can be represented as a set of smaller subimages cropped from it, or as sets of more complex image feature descriptions.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] (2001) use MinHash as a tool for association rule learning.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] The MinHash algorithm has been adapted for bioinformatics, where the problem of comparing genome sequences has a similar theoretical underpinning to that of comparing documents on the web.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] MinHash-based tools allow rapid comparison of whole genome sequencing data with reference genomes (around 3 minutes to compare one genome with the 90000 reference genomes in RefSeq), and are suitable for speciation and maybe a limited degree of microbial sub-typing.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] There are also applications for metagenomics and the use of MinHash derived algorithms for genome alignment and genome assembly.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Accurate average nucleotide identity (ANI) values can be generated very efficiently with MinHash-based algorithms.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] In this instance, the signature of a set may be seen as its hash value.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] Other locality sensitive hashing techniques exist for Hamming distance between sets and cosine distance between vectors; locality sensitive hashing has important applications in nearest neighbor search algorithms.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] For large distributed systems, and in particular MapReduce, there exist modified versions of MinHash to help compute similarities with no dependence on the point dimension.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] A large scale evaluation was conducted by Google in 2006 to compare the performance of Minhash and SimHash algorithms.
[src:probabilistic-sketches/minhash] In 2007 Google reported using Simhash for duplicate detection for web crawling and using Minhash and LSH for Google News personalization.
